A board game puzzler, like Hitman Go. But unlike Hitman Go, this feels more free-form and less like a blocky board game. Replayability isn't quite as good, since once you've beaten a puzzle, there's little incentive to go back except to find hidden collectibles, but just playing through once is an experience worth the $5 price tag.

The 'Lara Croft GO' puzzle adventure is a beautifully rendered 3D simulator game, much like traditional first-person 3D adventure games with convincingly immersive graphics to propel the player into the three-dimensional environments employing an excellent perspective view.  Unlike traditional 3D roaming adventure games, Lara Croft GO utilises limited movement along the four diagonal vertices representing the West, East and North, South directions. This forces emphasis on the player to solve puzzles rather than wandering aimlessly within the playing field. The graphics are exquisitely drawn with incredible detail to capture the realism to effectively convince the player that they are actually within these precarious environments of gorgeous symmetry along with their delightful and highly intricate and detailed playing fields. The game's adversaries too, the giant snakes and spiders along with the nasty lizards show evidence of extreme detail and intricate texture.  The hazardous adversaries often appear at crucial junctures, whereby nearby obstacles are deliberately placed to allude and delude anyone daring enough to tackle. The game is certainly a work of art by any means.  A game utilizing gorgeous graphics with impressive atmospheric audio accompaniment that will entice the player throughout the adventure. A fun game to play.  The game's overall performance is remarkable. Its bountiful sophisticated visual graphic appeal is evident of the high-calibre of people responsible for creating such an entertaining and beautiful game. The imaginative and talented programmers whom have created such an extraordinary 3D isometric simulation must have spent months in creating Lara Croft GO, taking into account of the vast intricate optical physics and mechanical discrepancies to consider. A delightfully well crafted game for the entire family. Definitely a Five Star rating!

Amazing Unique Puzzle Game. I was reluctant to buy it at first as I seen the word 'GO' in the title and thought it would be more action packed or have some endless runner theme to it.. I was wrong! Very unique twist on the lara croft games while still retaining the feel of them. The puzzles are extreamly well designed and there's bonus collectables to look out for A lot of effort was put into this game and it shows, some of the beggining levels are too easy but the last 2 bonus worlds get very very difficult, but not in a frustrating way. Completely worth the price.. I've probably spent around 10 hours to complete it 100%. If you're a fan of the puzzle genre don't miss this.

Wow. The game is fantastic! Everything the description for the game tells you is right. The aesthetics in the game are beautiful. They're so intriguing! They tell so much story. The level design is where the game REALLY shines. So much thought and effort was put into it. Although 1 or 2 of the later levels gets on your nerves because you can't solve it, it doesn't make you hate the game. Additionally, there are collectables in the game that give you some cool outfits. They're not just there for the sake of being there. Even those collectables have their own charm. They feel like they belong. The McGiffins, for the lack of a better word, have mystery to them although you don't get to keep them. Lastly, the music is fantastic. It always makes you wonder or fear whatever is going on and is outstanding!! Square Enix made one of the best mobile games and I'm one of the people that is going to support them and trust them to make the best games.

This will be the FIRST EVER review I'm gonna be giving an app (and a game 
at that no less) here on Google Play store. I usually don't have the 
inclination to give a rating, much more write a review. But this time I 
simply MUST because the game gave me a good feeling and happines and that I 
once again recalled when I first played a similar puzzle adventure in my PC 
gaming days. I concur with all the other GREAT REVIEWS given here. A game 
doesn't have to have all the bells and whistles graphics-wise to be good. 
Moreover, I find beauty in the simplicity of the game graphics that doesn't 
distract the gameplay and that which adds to the soothing ambiance along 
with the great BGM composition. The swipe control works well for me, even 
though I'm a traditional gamepad gamer. I'm mightly impressed by the 
execution of bringing this game onto this platform. I know that this 
request may be a long shot but if you guys could also do a Prince of Persia 
(the PC game that got me hooked into puzzle adventures) GO edition I would 
buy it in a heartbeat. I paid for an ordinary (and a discounted one at 
that) sum but got a GEM in return. Great price, best purchase. THANK YOU 
VERY MUCH.

This is one of the best Android games I have ever played, and it ranks on my list of best games period. SE really got the feel of Lara almost perfect, and all the elements lined up to make this a great experience. The graphics, while initially "primitive" actually work really well. The environments are beautiful in a minimalist fashion. The music is calming (which is helpful) and fades into the background. Even the animations of the characters are good. The puzzles themselves aren't terribly difficult, but they do require you to think ahead several steps, and in multiple dimensions (something that was lost in Deus Ex Go). I only had to get hints twice, but I thoroughly enjoyed every puzzle right to the end. My only real complaints are that you get the last two artifact/gem pieces (for the outfits) as you literally finish the game, but I could see replaying this at some point once my memory fades, so that's pretty minor.

Lara Croft GO draws deep inspiration from the Tomb Raider franchise to create a brilliant turn-based puzzle game for mobile devices. Beautiful animated graphics provide a bird's eye view of each level so that you can plan your problem-solving strategy, while the exceptionally creative soundtrack provides the perfect ambient music for each stage of the game. The level of difficulty starts out easy and gradually increases until it becomes fiendishly challenging in the final chapter. The puzzles are thoroughly enjoyable and phenomenally ingenious. They sometimes seem impossible to solve, but they always have a logical solution! For about $2, you can buy permanent access to built-in hints for all the puzzles. If you get stuck, these hints‚Äã guide you one step at a time so that you can solve the rest of the puzzle yourself. App navigation is a joy and the icons are intuitive and elegant. I replayed the last three chapters just to master the strategic, analytical, and creative thinking the game teaches you. Now I'm eager to play the whole Square Enix GO series. Bring it on! :)

The game isn't terrible, but it features a "real" Lara Croft and temple instead of a game piece and a gameboard. The charm of Hitman Go lay in the reinterpretation of the dark characters, activities, and environs through the aggressively bright and cheerful lens of a family-friendly board game, a perfect little world inhabited by perfect little people who never stray from their perfect little paths. Take that away and all you've got is a mediocre third-person adventure game. I wish I could return this app; I hate that my money has gone to further this mistaken attempt at a franchise.

Very good sequel to Hitman Go, with more varied mechanics that makes the game feel less repetitive than the previous episode. Game feels as difficult as its predecessor, and the lifetime is roughly the same, maybe shorter. Graphics have also been improved and are one of the high points of the game, although the aliasing is very noticeable. Animations are sometimes buggy (especially the monsters' when you play fast), and sometimes the character takes an awful lot of time to climb an edge. Overall, worth every penny of the dollar and a half I paid for it. Talking about money, Square is getting greedy with the in-app purchases, which now cost a couple dollars while they are free in Hitman Go. This is a very surprising decision considering this is the kind of content one generally looks for on the internet and doesn't even expect to have in the game in the first place.

I bought this game thinking it would be like Hitman Go, but it turns out to be quite different - Lara Croft Go is very heavily influenced by Monument Valley, and although it lacks the charm and depth of that game, it steals certain elements of its gameplay and graphical design. I like the addition of sub-quests, such as finding pots of treasure hidden in the undergrowth (some of them only reveal themselves when the player reaches a certain part of the screen) but some parts of the game seem a bit silly, for instance Lara can shoot snakes from behind or from the side, but not from the front, even when standing a mere two squares away from the slithery beasts. What, Lara Croft can't shoot pistols from 10ft away?! The latest update (Aug 2016) is a travesty. Suddenly what's ostensibly a bug fix release is asking for access to your contacts, including email addresses and phone numbers. Why? So that Square Enix can harvest your data, build a network and sell it, one assumes. And I hear that the update causes huge instability issues. So basically I'm updating the game ever again.

This is one of the absolute best mobile games I have ever played. This game is outstanding. I am a casual gamer (for mobile anyways) that loves art in games. The art in this game is perfectly crafted. I find myself staring at almost every frame as if it were a painting. Each with muted or under saturated colors of flat surfaces, pots, and vegetation, colorful, but intimidating, reptilian foes you can foil with simple tricks using your imagination, and beautiful, independently moving, layers of backgrounds that make you feel like you are actually in the tombs with Lara. The music is ambient and adds to the, deep, almost dark, thought provoking experience. The soundtrack is free in case anyone was interested on SoundCloud.   Besides the art, the game play, I feel, is superior to Hitman Go. It is still a masterfully blended mix of perfect parts of influence from classic games like Go (Japanese game of war), Chess, and even Mazes. You are not restricted to the complicated objectives that are found in Hitman Go, such as "in less than N turns", or "without killing anyone" and you are free to play through, iff you can complete each level to unlock the barriers to the next.   Thank you

replyContent:
Hi Karl,

We're unsure we understand your concern, but Lara Croft GO is a turn-based game and Lara only moves one step at a time. You are not meant to move like in a traditional Tomb Raider game, each step could mean death for Lara so you really want to be careful. 

Hope this answers your question! Thanks!

Play this first, and if you like it and want something harder play Hitman Go afterward.

Lara Croft GO is an abstract turn-based puzzle game wrapped in beautiful graphics and animations true to the familiar Tomb Raider setting. The core mechanics are of an elegant simplicity, and although puzzles start out fairly easy, they gradually become more challenging as the game progresses.  The game features solid design fundamentals: the environment reacts in a predictable way to Lara's movements, allowing the player to plot out a solution strategy in advance. New enemies and game mechanics are introduced in a way that allows the player to learn how they work, before incorporating them into more complicated puzzles. Levels contain savepoints at sensible locations, which prevents players from solving the same puzzle over and over. The result is a smooth, highly enjoyable gameplay experience.  Although the base game is fairly short, an expansion called The Shard of Life is included for free. This expansion contains another set of relatively difficult puzzles, and guarantees plenty of value for your money.

This game just proves that free to play isn't always the best way to go about gamemaking. Lara Croft GO brings the familiar action vibe into a turn-based puzzle form, with you moving Lara step by step through a mazelike level to reach the goal. Along the way, you might find that moving blades block your path, but instead of constantly moving, here they only move when you do, so you have to learn the patterns as you move in order to dodge them. Killing snakes that block your path require approaching them from the right direction in order to kill them. Finding relics and gems gives you new outfits. It might be hard to describe in writing, but it is absolutely worth your time to check it out. Cool stuff S-E Montreal!

I don't usually play Mobile OS games, actually in fact, I hate them honestly. But, I see why at the Game Awards this year, it was nominated for best Mobile OS game. I love the Lara Croft games, and this one to me hits my love of puzzle games. Lara Croft GO offers a great variety of puzzles to solve to get from Point A to Point B. Sometimes there can even be a challenge along the way to point B. Snakes, Lizards, Spiders and more will try to get in your way. You as the players have to look and use your wits to get through the puzzle. Along the way tapping on jars to discovery precious gems like Diamonds, Sapphires and Emeralds will build a collection. If your lucky you can find a piece to even bigger prize like a statues once you collect all pieces that is. But, to keep simple this game is pretty awesome for a Mobile OS game for either Android OS. The graphics looks beautiful for a mobile device. The music is relaxing and calming and simply put I enjoy it. Great title to pick up if your ever bored and need something quick to play.

I've never played a Tomb Raider or Hitman game, but I love the Go games. The puzzles so far are interesting in the way they teach and tickle the brain, and the hunt for relic prices lends itself to a natural pause in the main game when the player is ready to hunt. I highly recommend this game.

You are stuck moving on locations marked with small diamonds.  You don't get to explore anything; your'e on rails. All of the freedom and responsiveness of the original is lost.  The puzzles are boring.  And here's the truly unbelievable part: if you "win," that is, if you solve puzzles, what reward do you get?  New weapons?  New areas to explore?  No.  You get clothes.  For Lara Croft.  Who is so tiny I can barely see here on a 7-inch tablet.  Yes, folks, Lara Croft brought to you by The Sims.  I have never spent more on an Android game, and I have never enjoyed a paid game less.
